<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1648,2010]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,284,1648,1674]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Scutellum with six yellow bristles each side, wing pale brown at tip and dark brown at base. Dorsum of abdomen with dense long yellow hairs and posterior portion of tergites 
<number box="[1146,1192,1685,1711]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3–7</number>
with yellow bristles with dark brown tips. Epandrium irregularly formed in lateral view; epiphallus subtriangular, obtuse at tip in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1648,2010]" box="[197,901,1797,1823]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,349,1797,1823]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Body length 
<quantity box="[582,653,1797,1823]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
, wing length 
<quantity box="[811,896,1797,1823]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1648,2010]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[277,350,1834,1860]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 11" captionStartId="12.[151,273,1829,1853]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,199,1771]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,194,1808]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 11. Anastoechus heads, 1. Anastoechus asiaticus Becker; 2. Anastoechus aurecrinitus Yang et Du; 3. Anastoechus candidus sp. nov.; 4. Anastoechus chakanus Du et al.; 5. Anastoechus chinensis Paramonov; 6. Anastoechus doulananus Du et al.; 7. Anastoechus fulvus sp. nov.; 8. Anastoechus turriformis sp. nov.; 9. Anastoechus xuthus sp. nov.; 10. Anastoechus neimongolanus Du &amp; Yang." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195261/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Fig. 
<number box="[334,350,1834,1860]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
) black with brown dust. Hairs on head black and white; frons narrowing directed distally, with long dense black and white erect hairs and short white scales, face with long dense white erect hairs; occiput with long sparse black erect hairs and white scales near edge of eyes. Antenna black except yellow at joint; scape elongate with long dense white and black hairs; first flagellomere elongate, with brown scales close to base, with a stylus at tip. Proboscis black, bare, nearly four times longer than head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,1151]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Thorax black with pale dust. Hairs on thorax mostly yellow; postpronotal lobe with long dense yellow hairs, mesonotum with long dense yellow hairs; thorax almost bare on back, anepisternum and katepisternum with long dense white hairs. Scutellum black, with six yellow bristles each side. Leg [mid and hind legs broken] brown except femur black. Hairs on legs mostly white, bristles yellow. Femur with dense white hairs and scales; tibia and tarsus with short yellow hairs and brown scales. Fore tibia with seven 
<emphasis box="[1222,1251,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">ad</emphasis>
, eight 
<emphasis box="[1333,1362,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">pd</emphasis>
, eight 
<emphasis box="[151,177,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">av</emphasis>
, nine 
<emphasis box="[248,274,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">pv</emphasis>
. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[367,452,338,364]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 20" captionStartId="13.[151,272,1649,1673]" captionTargetBox="[151,1396,248,1578]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,197,1624]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 20. Anastoechus wings, dorsal view. 11. Anastoechus asiaticus Becker; 12. Anastoechus aurecrinitus Yang et Du; 13. Anastoechus candidus sp. nov.; 14. Anastoechus chakanus Du et al.; 15. Anastoechus chinensis Paramonov; 16. Anastoechus doulananus Du et al.; 17. Anastoechus fulvus sp. nov.; 18. Anastoechus turriformis sp. nov.; 19. Anastoechus xuthus sp. nov.; 20. Anastoechus neimongolanus Du &amp; Yang." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195262/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[422,452,338,364]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
) uniformly pale brown except base dark brown. Vein r-m close to tip of cell dm, cell r 
<number box="[161,169,392,406]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="5.0">5</number>
closed. Base of vein C with brush-like long black bristles and white scales and hairs. Halteres black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,1151]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Abdomen black. Hairs on abdomen mostly yellow; dorsum with long dense yellow hairs and posterior of tergites 
<number box="[244,287,453,479]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="5.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="3.0">3–7</number>
with dark brown tip yellow bristles. Sternites black with white dust and long dense white hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,1151]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[384,530,490,516]" captionStart="FIGURES 67 – 72" captionStartId="22.[151,271,1643,1667]" captionTargetBox="[158,1422,214,1597]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,194,1621]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 67 – 72. Anastoechus xuthus sp. nov. male genitalia. 67. epandrium and cercus, dorsal view; 68. epandrium and cercus, lateral view; 69. gonocoxite and gonostylus, lateral view; 70. phallus, dorsal view; 71. phallus, lateral view; 72. gonocoxite and gonostyli, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195271/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Figs. 
<number box="[451,530,490,516]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="69.5" valueMax="72.0" valueMin="67.0">67–72</number>
</figureCitation>
). Epandrium trapezoidal, distinctly longer than high; cercus well exposed in lateral view; epandrium a little longer than wide, almost parallel two sides in dorsal view; gonocoxite with black bristle-like hairs apically, tumid near base and parallel two sides from middle to tip in ventral view; gonostylus elongate, its tip acute in lateral view; epiphallus subtriangular, obtuse at tip in dorsal view, epiphallus with a long and curved tip in lateral view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,152,1151]" box="[197,421,677,703]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
